:"circa 1403","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","about 1385":"circa 1385","1439":"1439","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Besthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Besthorpe, Norfolk, England","of Besthrope, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1385–1420":"about 1385–1420","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1385–Female":"1385–Deceased","1410–1439":"1410–1439","1345–1375":"1345–1375","1350–Female":"1350–Deceased","1345":"1345","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","Abt 1403":"about 1403","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","about 1385":"about 1385","1439":"1439","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Besthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Besthorpe, Norfolk, England","of Besthrope, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Denston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Denstone (Staffs).","2  English: locative name from Denston (Suffolk), which is recorded as  <i>Denardeston</i> in 1220."],"variants":[{"name":"Deniston","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Denniston  .","English: variant of <b>Denston</b>, a habitational name from either Denstone in Staffordshire (named from the Old English personal name <i>Deni</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘estate, farmstead’ meaning ‘farmstead of a man called Deni’), or from Denston in Suffolk (from the Old English personal name <i>Deneheard</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead of a man called Deneheard’)."]},{"name":"Denstone","meanings":["English:  See  Denston  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Denston I was born about 1385, in Norfolk, England, his father, John Denston, was 41 and his mother, Mrs John Denston, was 37. He married Mrs. William Denston I about 1403, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1420, in Besthorpe, Norfolk, England, at the age of 36."},"et":{"about 1385–1420":"umbes 1385–1420","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","1410–1439":"1410–1439","1345–1375":"1345–1375","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1345":"1345","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","Abt 1403":"umbes 1403","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","about 1385":"umbes 1385","1439":"1439","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Besthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Besthorpe, Norfolk, England","of Besthrope, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1385–1420":"noin 1385–1420","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1385–Female":"1385–Kuollut","1410–1439":"1410–1439","1345–1375":"1345–1375","1350–Female":"1350–Kuollut","1345":"1345","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","Abt 1403":"noin 1403","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","about 1385":"noin 1385","1439":"1439","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Besthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Besthorpe, Norfolk, England","of Besthrope, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1385–1420":"environ 1385–1420","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1385–Female":"1385–Décédée","1410–1439":"1410–1439","1345–1375":"1345–1375","1350–Female":"1350–Décédée","1345":"1345","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","Abt 1403":"environ 1403","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","about 1385":"environ 1385","1439":"1439","N